    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 3.84,
      "text": "This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 4.68,
      "end": 8.66,
      "text": "For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 10.06,
      "end": 15.2,
      "text": "Esop's Fable, Jupiter and the Tortoise, read by Patrick McNeil, Bakersfield, California.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 16.88,
      "end": 21.78,
      "text": "Jupiter was about to marry a wife and determined to celebrate the event by inviting all the animals",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 21.78,
      "end": 27.34,
      "text": "to a banquet. They all came except the tortoise who did not put in an appearance, much to Jupiter's",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 27.34,
      "end": 32.28,
      "text": "surprise. So when he next saw the tortoise, he asked him why he had not been at the banquet.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 33.14,
      "end": 37.48,
      "text": "I don't care for going out, said the tortoise. There's no place like home.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 38.64,
      "end": 43.02,
      "text": "Jupiter was so much annoyed by this reply that he decreed that from that time forth",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 43.02,
      "end": 47.5,
      "text": "the tortoise should carry his house upon his back and never be able to get away from home,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 48.12,
      "end": 50.96,
      "text": "even if he wished to. End of Fable.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
